tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div b font span
content: Former CIA Agent Michael Scheuer, on Iraq

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div b span
html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div span
content: Iraqi officials said Saturday they are considering new measures to protect voters in the Jan. 30 national election, including a three-day, nationwide ban on driving to discourage car-bombings.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div span
content: Fresh clashes broke out in the troubled northern city of Mosul, where most election officials have fled their jobs in fear. A U.S. military helicopter made an emergency landing in Mosul after drawing ground fire, the U.S. command said.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div span
content: Also, a U.S. Marine was killed in action Saturday in a tense area just south of Baghdad; the U.S. military claimed insurgents are being aided by former Saddam Hussein loyalists now in Syria; and leading Shiite politicians tried to dispel fears they would impose an Iranian-style clerical regime and appealed to Sunnis to participate in balloting.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div span
content: U.S. and Iraqi officials fear a surge in insurgent attacks as the election approaches. Many members of the Sunni Arab minority are expected to boycott the balloting, and Sunni rebel groups have threatened to attack polling stations.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div span
content: To prevent that, an Iraqi Cabinet minister told reporters that authorities are considering a number of special measures, including restrictions on the movement of private vehicles, and possible security cordons around polling stations.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div span
content: Provincial Affairs minister Waeil Abdel-Latif gave no details about the proposed restrictions, but security officials said they included banning all private vehicle traffic across the country for three days around the election. That would make it easier to spot would-be vehicle bombers and to inhibit rebel movements.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div span
content: "The government is determined to make available facilities and security guarantees to ensure the success of the election," Abdel-Latif said.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div b span
html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Army Spc. Charles Graner Jr., the suspected ringleader of abuse at the Abu Ghraib prison in Iraq,

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li a span
content: took the stand for the first time Saturday

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: and said he was ordered by interrogators to physically mistreat and sexually humiliate prisoners. Speaking a day after his conviction for the abuse, Graner described himself as a by-the-book prison guard who was corrupted by superiors.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Three mortar shells exploded Saturday near Baghdad's heavily guarded Green Zone, causing no casualties but sending American and Iraqi officials scurrying for cover. It marked the third straight day of rebel attacks on the Green Zone, the nerve center of the U.S. and Iraqi administration, after a lull of a couple of weeks.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: A roadside bomb ripped through a U.S. convoy Saturday on the western edge of Baghdad, destroying a truck, police Lt. Akram al-Zubaie said. There were no reports of casualties.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: U.S. troops arrested six suspected insurgents, including a former Iraqi general, in raids around Baghdad early Saturday, U.S. officials said. The general, who was not identified, was suspected of planning insurgent attacks.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Underscoring the security threat, fresh clashes broke out Saturday in the troubled northern city of Mosul between U.S. troops and insurgents, after the rebels blasted an American convoy.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: After the blast, insurgents opened fire on American troops, who then raided a nearby agricultural research station looking for the assailants.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: A U.S. Army OH58 Kiowa helicopter made an emergency landing in Mosul, Iraq's third-largest city, after receiving ground fire. The two crew members escaped injury, the command said.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: In Baghdad, Brig. Gen. Carter Ham, the U.S. general responsible for security in northern Iraq, said that virtually every election worker in Ninevah province, which includes Mosul, quit recently because of security fears.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Ham said a new election coordinator was scrambling to find workers with about two weeks left before the election and that staffers may have to be sent there from other parts of the country.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: "To tell you the truth, we don't know how many staff there actually were," he told reporters. "But we know that at one point, there were essentially none left."

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Ham also said there were indications that insurgents were getting support from Iraqis who fled to Syria, about 70 miles west of Mosul, after Saddam's regime collapsed.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: "There are some indications, clearly, that the insurgency is receiving some support from former regime forces that are based in Syria," Ham said, echoing allegations by Iraqi officials.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Security fears and opposition within the Sunni community have led to calls by some Sunni politicians to delay the election, a proposal strongly rejected by the U.S. administration and the country's powerful Shiite clerical hierarchy.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Iraqis will choose a 275-member parliament as well as provincial administrations. Voters in the Kurdish autonomous region will also select a new regional parliament.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: However, U.S. and Iraqi officials fear that a low Sunni turnout could cast doubt on the new government's legitimacy. Many Sunni Arabs, who make up an estimated 20 percent of Iraq's nearly 26 million people, fear a loss of political power to the Shiites � an estimated 60 percent of the population.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: During a press conference Saturday, leading Shiite politicians sought to dispel fears they would impose an Iranian-style clerical regime and appealed to Sunnis to participate in balloting.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: "The issue is who do you want to obey � Saddam Hussein, Osama bin Laden ... or the Iraqi people," said Mouwaffaq al-Rubaie, the government's national security adviser. "There is no intention or plan to form an Islamic or religious state in Iraq ... or an Iranian style government."

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Shiite candidate Ahmad Chalabi, once the Pentagon's choice to rule Iraq, said he planned to meet with Sunni leaders to encourage them to vote.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: "I believe that this impression that the Sunnis will not vote will be dispelled quickly," he said. "They will vote."

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: In another development Saturday, the Defense Ministry confirmed a report in a major Arabic daily that an Iraqi woman trained by members of Saddam's regime in Syria tried to assassinate the defense minister but fainted before carrying out her mission.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Al Hayat newspaper quoted Defense Minister Hazem Shaalan as saying the assassination attempt took place in his Baghdad office more than a week ago.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: Shaalan told the newspaper that the woman, who is about 40, entered the ministry claiming she wanted to deliver important security information.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td div li span
content: "As she was sitting in the presence of several officials from the ministry, she surprised everyone by taking out a pistol she was carrying and pointed it at me from a distance of about one meter, but in the last moment she collapsed and started crying," he was quoted as saying.

tag: html body text table tbody tr td table tbody tr td span span
